# Orfeo ToolBox with Tensorflow v2

Summary of the approach:

The Orfeo ToolBox is an open source library for remote sensing image processing, containing about a hundred user-oriented applications including geometric and radiometric corrections, image manipulation, and statistics. It provides multiple interfaces like command line, graphical user interface, and third-party software like QGIS, and eases the integration and deployment of new features for developers.
TensorFlow is a high-performance numerical computation library for training and inference on deep neural networks, with a powerful high-level Python API to build deep nets. The OTBTF remote module of the Orfeo ToolBox supports the interaction between remote sensing and deep learning, allowing users without programming skills to use deep nets on remote sensing images. Deep learning experts can still use their coding skills to build/train their models using their favorite API and use the SavedModel in OTBTF to produce their resulting geospatial images.
Patch-based classification is a task of classifying image patches of fixed size and attributing the estimated class to the central pixel of the patch to produce a land cover map. It is based on patch-based classification for land cover mapping, and can be used with remote sensing images.
A simple convolutional neural network can be used to train a deep learning model for remote sensing image analysis. The smaller the batch, the more accurate the estimate of the gradient will be, but if the number of samples is too small, the gradient changes its direction very often compared to a bigger batch. The goal of the training is to minimize the cross entropy between the data distribution (real labels) and the model distribution (estimated labels).
The Fully Convolutional Neural Networks (FCNN) can process entire image regions instead of being limited to small patches, making them faster than patch-based CNNs. However, pooling layers in FCNNs can completely destroy the resolution of the output, so modifications to the original model are needed to create a pixel-wise fully convolutional network.
The PatchesExtraction application can be used to extract patches in an image and label image jointly. The output raster contains integer values between 0 and the number of classes minus one. This application is useful for creating training and validation datasets for deep learning models.
The usual metrics to evaluate a classification map include precision, F-score, and accuracy for each class, as well as overall kappa index and accuracy. These metrics are important for assessing the performance of a deep learning model in semantic segmentation tasks.
The approach for image restoration using deep learning has shown superior results compared to traditional gap-filling methods. The network used in this approach is based on the U-Net architecture and is trained on a dataset of patches extracted from Sentinel-2 and Sentinel-1 images.
